At this level, classes specialized from other classes, which may or may not be a derived schema element (for example OM_Process is not a defined schema element, whereas TM_Process does define a schema element). This means that these constraints may be later combined with constraints from another profile, which defines a schema element. This leads to three possible outcomes: 1) a single schema element is defined and all constraints can be applied to it 2) no schema element have been defined for these constraints and further level of profiling is required before it can be implemented 3) incompatible schemas are identified and the constraint cannot be satisfied
Note that different implmentation platforms, e.g. GML or RDF, might have different constraints around schema validity. Thus, it might be possible that a profile can be implemented in RDF, but not in XML Schema.
This implies that helper machinery is properly required to collate and validate profile hierarchies to support the schema generation for the various implementation platforms.
